Dynamic elements wo elements hote hain jinke attributes (id, class, etc.) har page load par change ho jate hain.
Inhe handle karne ke liye Selenium me flexible locators aur XPath techniques use ki jati hain.

Using Dynamic XPath (contains())

Agar element ka attribute change hota hai to partial value use karte hain.

Example HTML:

<input id="user_12345">

Next time:

<input id="user_56789">

Selenium code:

driver.findElement(By.xpath("//input[contains(@id,'user')]"));
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Using starts-with()

Agar attribute same prefix se start ho raha ho.

driver.findElement(By.xpath("//input[starts-with(@id,'user')]"));
3️⃣ Using text() Method

Agar element text stable hai to text use kar sakte hain.

driver.findElement(By.xpath("//button[text()='Login']"));
4️⃣ Using CSS Selector

CSS selector bhi dynamic elements handle karne me help karta hai.

driver.findElement(By.cssSelector("input[id^='user']"));

^= → starts with

5️⃣ Using Explicit Wait

Kabhi kabhi element late load hota hai, isliye wait use karte hain.

WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(10));

wait.until(ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElementLocated(By.id("username")));
6️⃣ Using Parent or Sibling XPath

Agar element ka direct attribute change hota hai to parent ya sibling relation use karte hain.

driver.findElement(By.xpath("//label[text()='Username']/following-sibling::input"));
Interview Me Short Answer

Agar interviewer puche to aise bolo:

Dynamic elements can be handled using dynamic XPath techniques such as contains() and starts-with(), 
CSS selectors, explicit waits, and by locating elements using stable attributes or relationships like parent and sibling.
